⚡ Quick Summary of AJAX
AJAX = Asynchronous JavaScript and XML

It’s a technique (not a language) used in web development.

Purpose: Send/receive data from a server without reloading the page.

Commonly used with JSON instead of XML today.

Example: When you type in Google search, results update instantly — that’s AJAX.

✅ 20 Quick Q&A on AJAX
Basics
Q: What does AJAX stand for?
A: Asynchronous JavaScript and XML.

Q: Is AJAX a programming language?
A: No, it’s a technique.

Q: What’s the main purpose of AJAX?
A: Update parts of a webpage without reloading.

Q: Which technologies does AJAX combine?
A: JavaScript, HTML, CSS, DOM, and server-side scripts.

Q: What’s commonly used instead of XML today?
A: JSON.

Functionality
Q: How does AJAX communicate with the server?
A: Using XMLHttpRequest or fetch().

Q: Is AJAX synchronous or asynchronous?
A: Asynchronous (non-blocking).

Q: Can AJAX work with PHP, ASP.NET, or Node.js?
A: Yes, it works with any server-side language.

Q: Does AJAX require page refresh?
A: No.

Q: What’s a real-life example of AJAX?
A: Live search suggestions on Google.

Advantages
Q: Why is AJAX faster?
A: It only updates parts of the page, not the whole.

Q: Does AJAX improve user experience?
A: Yes, smoother and more interactive.

Q: Can AJAX reduce server load?
A: Yes, fewer full-page requests.

Q: Is AJAX compatible with modern browsers?
A: Yes.

Q: Can AJAX send both GET and POST requests?
A: Yes.

Limitations
Q: Does AJAX work if JavaScript is disabled?
A: No.

Q: Can AJAX affect SEO?
A: Yes, if content isn’t crawlable.

Q: Is AJAX secure by itself?
A: No, security must be handled server-side.

Q: Can AJAX handle large data?
A: Yes, but performance depends on server and network.

Q: Is AJAX still relevant today?
A: Yes, often combined with frameworks like React, Angular, and Vue.
